CARACAS â€“ Gold held by Venezuela's central bank fell 14% in value in 2017 compared with the previous year, according to the bank's financial statement. Gold represents just under 70% of the bank's international reserves, which at the end of 2017 totaled $9.67-billion. The value of Venezuela's monetary gold stood at $6.63-billion as of December 2017, according to the most recent official information. The fall comes amid a major economic crisis in Venezuela, with millions suffering food shortages and the government struggling to import basic products. The central bank valued its reserves at $1 272.42/oz at the end of 2016 and $1 271.03/oz at the end of last year. The volume of gold fell 16% to 5.2 -million troy ounces at the end of 2017. In 2014, the central bank began swapping monetary gold in order to obtain liquidity with which to curb a sharp economic crisis. In October, Venezuela allowed a $1.7-billion gold swap with Germany's Deutsche Bank to lapse, according to an opposition legislator.